name: 6-[bis(5-ethylfuran-2-yl)methyl]-7-nitro-2,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodioxine
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2671
Reason: We will examine the melting point of 6-[bis(5-ethylfuran-2-yl)methyl]-7-nitro-2,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodioxine by considering the effects of its functional groups on the basic benzene structure. Starting with benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C, we will add or subtract value estimates for each functional group present in the target molecule. Ethyl groups typically add about +20°C due to the increase in molecular weight and van der Waals forces. Two furan rings present are likely to increase the melting point by about +20°C each, as oxygen heteroatoms participate in dipole interactions and the rings add rigidity to the molecule. The methyl group might contribute around +15°C because of the added van der Waals interactions. The nitro group is highly electronegative, which can increase melting point due to stronger intermolecular forces; adding perhaps +30°C. The 1,4-benzodioxine structure, encompassing a benzene ring with two oxygen atoms, might add an additional +25°C as it also increases rigidity and allows for hydrogen bonding between molecules. However, due to conjugation and resonance stabilization that would lower the overall energy state of the compound, we should subtract a small amount, say -10°C, for the combined effect of the aromatic systems including benzene, furan rings, and the benzodioxine system. Summing these adjustments, we get an estimated value for the melting point. Benzene (5.5) + 2 Furan rings (2 * 20) + 2 Ethyl groups (2 * 20) + Methyl group (15) + Nitro group (30) + 1,4-benzodioxine (25) - Conjugation (10) = 5.5 + 40 + 40 + 15 + 30 + 25 - 10 = 145.5°C
